  "topic_name": "Study of Water",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Water (H2O) is a bent/angular molecule with bond angle 104.5 degrees. Hydrogen bonding between water molecules causes unique properties. Water has maximum density at 4 degrees C and expands on freezing (anomalous behavior), allowing ice to float and aquatic life to survive in frozen lakes. Water is called the universal solvent. It reacts with metals to form hydroxides, with non-metals to form acids. Hard water contains dissolved Ca/Mg salts: temporary hardness (bicarbonates) is removed by boiling; permanent hardness (sulfates, chlorides) is removed by adding washing soda or ion exchange.",
    "rules": [
      "Water molecule: H2O, bent shape, bond angle 104.5 degrees",
      "Maximum density at 4 degrees C",
      "Anomalous expansion: water expands on freezing",
      "Universal solvent due to polarity",
      "Temporary hardness: Ca(HCO3)2, Mg(HCO3)2 - removed by boiling",
      "Permanent hardness: CaSO4, CaCl2 - removed by washing soda",
      "Hydrogen bonding causes high boiling point",
      "Electrolysis: 2H2O -> 2H2 + O2"
    ]
  },
